    fullBio: "Michael Phelps is widely regarded as the greatest Olympian of all time and possibly the greatest competitive athlete who has ever lived. Born in Baltimore, Maryland in 1985, Phelps discovered swimming at age 7 after his sisters joined a local swim team. By 15, he was an Olympic bronze medalist. By 19, he had won six gold medals in Athens. By 23, he had become the most decorated Olympic athlete in history at a single Games — eight golds in Beijing 2008, a record that may never be touched. His physical profile was almost inhuman: a 6'4\" wingspan on a 6'0\" frame, size 14 feet, double-jointed ankles, and a naturally low heart rate. But it was his mental architecture that made him truly singular. Phelps trained six days a week, five hours a day, for twenty years. His coach Bob Bowman designed training regimens so brutal that teammates nicknamed them 'main sets.' Phelps didn't just survive them — he thrived in them. He retired after Rio 2016 as the most decorated Olympian ever (28 medals), then attempted a comeback for Tokyo 2020 before retiring again. His post-swimming life has included advocacy, golf, and a candid documentary series about his struggles with depression and the pressures of sustained excellence.",
