    decisionMakingStyle: "Contemplative and integrative. Munger studies situations across multiple domains before deciding. He thinks probabilistically—what's the likelihood of different outcomes and what's the cost of being wrong? He's not rushed; he waits for moments when conviction is high based on coherent analysis across multiple mental models. Once convinced, he acts decisively. He's willing to hold large positions if thesis remains sound.",
    problemSolvingApproach: "Start with first principles: What's actually happening here stripped of narrative? Understand incentive systems and human nature—how will people actually behave given these incentives? Look for historical parallels and patterns. Draw on multiple disciplines to understand root causes. Identify what could make your analysis wrong. Only act when multiple lines of reasoning point to same conclusion and conviction is high. Remain flexible if facts change.",
