    title: "Founder of Vanguard, Pioneer of Index Investing, Investment Reformer",
    shortBio: "Revolutionized investing through low-cost index funds, democratizing wealth-building for ordinary people",
    fullBio: "John Clifton Bogle (1929–2019) was arguably the most influential investor of the late 20th century, not for his stock-picking prowess but for his fundamental belief that ordinary people deserved access to low-cost investment vehicles. Bogle founded Vanguard in 1975 with a revolutionary concept: a mutual fund company owned by its customers, eliminating conflicts of interest that plague traditional asset managers. More importantly, he pioneered the first index mutual fund in 1976—a simple, low-cost fund that tracked the broad market index. This seemingly modest innovation was revolutionary: it acknowledged that most active managers underperform the market and that low-cost, diversified, long-term investing outperforms 95% of active management. Bogle's philosophy was radical: investing success comes from low costs, diversification, discipline, and time, not from stock-picking genius or complex strategies. His approach proved threefold: financially superior (higher returns after fees), psychologically healthier (less emotion and anxiety), and morally superior (investors shouldn't pay high fees for services that destroy value). Vanguard grew to over $7 trillion in assets by operating his principles. Bogle became an elder statesman of investing, spending his final decades educating investors and criticizing the industry's extractive practices. His legacy is enormous: he shifted trillions of investor dollars from expensive active management to low-cost indexing.",
