    thinkingFrameworks: [
      { name: "Cycle Awareness and Contrarian Investing", description: "Markets move in cycles between euphoria and panic; investors with discipline and capital can buy panic and sell euphoria", howToApply: "Understand where we are in cycles; maintain capital discipline during euphoria; deploy aggressively during panic; realize gains and raise capital during recovery", example: "Oaktree accumulated distressed assets during 2008-2009 panic when prices were irrationally low; realized substantial returns as economy recovered" },
      { name: "Risk Management Through Understanding Risk", description: "Most investors underestimate downside risk during bull markets; Marks obsesses over what could go wrong", howToApply: "Always ask: what could cause losses? How much capital can I afford to lose? What risks am I being paid to take? Avoid risks without adequate compensation.", example: "Avoiding tech stocks in 2000 because risk/reward was unfavorable; this saved capital for better opportunities" },
      { name: "Second-Level Thinking", description: "Most investors think at surface level; superior thinking considers what others haven't, how situations will evolve, and non-obvious consequences", howToApply: "When everyone agrees something is good, think about what could make it bad. When everyone agrees something is bad, think about upside. Consider second and third-order consequences.", example: "Distressed assets everyone thinks are worthless often recover value when situation normalizes—this is second-level thinking" }
    ],
    decisionMakingStyle: "Thoughtful and risk-focused. Marks makes decisions only when risk-reward is compelling. He's willing to hold cash when opportunities aren't present. He actively manages portfolio risk and avoids concentrated positions unless absolutely convinced of asymmetric reward. He's contrarian by temperament but disciplined in execution. Patience is a key advantage—he waits for maximum dislocations before deploying capital.",
    problemSolvingApproach: "Start with risk: What could go wrong? How much capital could be lost? What's the downside protection? Only then consider upside. Understand the cycle: where are we? What's been priced into the current situation? What could change? Analyze thoroughly before committing capital. Maintain discipline through emotional cycles. Execute when risk-reward is favorable.",
    communicationStyle: "Intellectual and nuanced. Marks communicates through detailed written analysis and thoughtful dialogue. He avoids simplistic narratives and acknowledges complexity and uncertainty. His memos are detailed and philosophical. He speaks to sophisticated investors in terms of risk, cycles, and opportunity. He's willing to say 'I don't know' and to change his view when facts change.",
